<div id="review_911129773" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/911129773" />
    <a title="Deborah Feingold" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/13464551-deborah-feingold"><img alt="Deborah Feingold" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1409111307p2/13464551.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/911129773?book_show_action=true">Apr 15, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Deborah Feingold" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Deborah Feingold" href="/user/show/13464551-deborah-feingold">Deborah Feingold</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13464551-deborah-feingold?shelf=poetry">poetry</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer911129773" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5239908159063190203">Kunitz helps the reader appreciate not only the importance of the garden as &quot;wilderness&quot; but of the necessity of accessing one&apos;s own wilderness, or unconscious, when composing poetry. I also loved his thoughts, linked metaphorically to his experience in the garden, about what is important to a poem. Rather than the showy flower, he is more interested in the underlying structure, the &quot;tensions and physicality.&quot; Finally this hybrid text, which presents many candid pictures of the hale nonagenarian</span>
  <span id="freeText5239908159063190203" style="display:none">Kunitz helps the reader appreciate not only the importance of the garden as "wilderness" but of the necessity of accessing one's own wilderness, or unconscious, when composing poetry. I also loved his thoughts, linked metaphorically to his experience in the garden, about what is important to a poem. Rather than the showy flower, he is more interested in the underlying structure, the "tensions and physicality." Finally this hybrid text, which presents many candid pictures of the hale nonagenarian, offers some important observations about aging; there is nothing sugar coated here, just the life force of a man who "loved the earth so much/ he wanted to stay forever."</span>
  <a data-text-id="5239908159063190203" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


