<div id="review_1056417287" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1056417287" />
    <a title="Nicole Perkins" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7443133-nicole-perkins"><img alt="Nicole Perkins" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1626206939p2/7443133.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1056417287?book_show_action=true">Sep 16, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nicole Perkins" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nicole Perkins" href="/user/show/7443133-nicole-perkins">Nicole Perkins</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1056417287" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1944464628161950363"> I have never read any of Stanley Kunitz&apos;s poetry before finding this book. This volume is a collection of essays interspersed with poems, written when Kunitz was one hundred years old, reflecting on garden life and metamorphosis. He draws parallels between tending the garden and tending the poetic spirit; Kunitz likens the cultivation and nurturing of plants to the creation and construction of a poem, all the while making the two so real, a tangible process that the mind and heart can fully und</span>
  <span id="freeText1944464628161950363" style="display:none"> I have never read any of Stanley Kunitz's poetry before finding this book. This volume is a collection of essays interspersed with poems, written when Kunitz was one hundred years old, reflecting on garden life and metamorphosis. He draws parallels between tending the garden and tending the poetic spirit; Kunitz likens the cultivation and nurturing of plants to the creation and construction of a poem, all the while making the two so real, a tangible process that the mind and heart can fully understand. This is a book I am going to be buying.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1944464628161950363" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


